40abb4f7d73ceadf087e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c41ab4521c4c2b6bde7b03ec4d9531acdc101f7e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a545f286136f5024bdadaa47d305e437cf32614f.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# How to create Sequential Workflows\n\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-create-sequential-workflows/4085\n\n@vikter (2026-01-08 13:05:14Z):\n   \n This article demonstrates how to create a simple sequential workflow with a user interface and a very simple XSL transformation involved. It also explains how to run and troubleshoot your workflows. \n \n [!success]- Prerequisites for proceeding \n To follow along, you must meet the following prerequisites: \n \n  Running database server  \n  Running ORIGAM Server  \n  Project created in ORIGAM Architect  \n  Entity with data created  \n \n \n As an example, we will use the  task manager from the initial tutorial . \n \n     To work with sequential workflows and business logic in general in ORIGAM, you need to understand the basics of the \u201CXML stack\u201D. If you are not familiar with the technologies involved, you may find the following video tutorials useful: \n \n  XML  \n  XSLT \u0026 XPath  \n \n \n   Introduction \n The application model in ORIGAM is physically stored in XML files. The main reason for this is that storing the model in files makes versioning and collaboration much easier than using a relational database. When modeling business logic, such as sequential workflows in this case, XML is also used in the background. This allows us to use XSL transformations for working with data in workflows. In addition, XPath is used to address XML elements entering the transformations. This is why familiarity with these languages is required when modeling business logic in ORIGAM. \n Technically, sequential workflows can be run by users or called by other business logic functional flows, for example by other workflows, or by an API call. Workflows available to users are located either in the main menu or as buttons in the toolbar. \n In this example, we will create a simple  workflow that assigns all selected tasks to the current user . \n   Workflow creation \n Our workflow will consist of the following steps: \n \n Load all existing tasks \n Select tasks \n Assign selected tasks to you \n Save changed tasks \n \n To create the workflow, go to the ORIGAM Architect, open the  Model Browser  tab, navigate to  Business Logic / Sequential Workflows / your package , right-click on your package and choose new  Sequential Workflow : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4f2e4067afd78693b6fd5c3508c2199f49a8b392.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface panel likely associated with a software application for managing workflows. The apparent context includes menu items under \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022User Interface,\u0022 and \u0022Business Logic,\u0022 with a specific focus on \u0022Sequential Workflows.\u0022 Visible UI text includes the following: \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022New Group,\u0022 and \u0022Repeat New F12,\u0022 along with the selected item \u0022Sequential Workflow.\u0022 The purpose of the interface appears to be facilitating the creation and management of sequential workflows, allowing users to add new workflows or groups efficiently.\n\n\n  \n What you get is: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/e9e1be37c3803900ad24f113ff1d41d0f8d9838d.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a sequential workflow configuration labeled \u0022TakeOverTasks.\u0022 It includes an info section with a schema item that lists properties such as \u0022Ancestors\u0022 set to False, \u0022Inheritable\u0022 set to False, and \u0022Name\u0022 defined as \u0022TakeOverTasks.\u0022 The tracing section contains two fields: \u0022Trace\u0022 with a value of No and \u0022Trace Level\u0022 set to InheritFromParent. The transactions section shows \u0022Transaction Behavior\u0022 as InheritExisting. On the right side, there are action buttons labeled \u0022Save\u0022 and \u0022Dock.\u0022 The overall purpose of this interface is to configure settings related to a sequential workflow process.\n\n\n  \n Name your workflow and optionally change the  Trace Level  to  Yes . This will allow you to debug your workflow later using the  Trace Tool . \n Now there are two possible actions: \n \n  Save  \u2013 saves the workflow and opens the workflow diagram editor \n  Dock  \u2013 opens it in the standard property editor, but without saving it \n \n For the purpose of this tutorial,  choose  Save . \n   Context Stores \n As any workflow usually operates with data, you need some kind of temporary \u201Cmemory\u201D to store that data. In ORIGAM, such a data repository is called a  Context store . \n Context stores take care of all data used across your workflow, and you need to create at least one. A Context store can be based on XML and linked to a specific Data Structure, which defines its structural content, or be a simple value defined by the data type (e.g. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-02T00:02:37"},"vector":[-0.037949927,-0.008742816,-0.06313328,0.028652795,0.00579162,0.011619398,-0.016895339,0.0145330485,0.0073624845,-0.00657818,0.015317228,-0.024865566,0.034525003,0.010280391,0.03212813,-0.024685556,-0.024537541,0.009762224,0.014251627,-0.0068926327,0.026714172,0.004840439,0.052855115,0.039034728,0.0152235925,0.041891344,-0.017346293,-0.022655185,-0.03964834,-0.00935206,-0.007752554,0.0054906923,0.0056509315,-0.018998994,-0.021329802,0.0049019237,-0.016252963,0.0014598353,-0.03917265,0.018150697,0.0019763429,0.018986948,0.008626375,0.011357368,0.008771817,-0.04653806,-0.017187085,-0.005585633,0.034925792,-0.071794294,-0.05419681,-0.006782668,0.03247313